"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-what-to-what-paris-olympics-august-9-soccer-gold-medal-match-breaking-debut\", \"text\": \"It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Day 14 of the Olympics. Just one more Friday and then the final two days fall over the weekend. There are tons of medals still left to be handed out, and once again I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m back with my daily watch guide to help you determine where to set your eyes.  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s also a great time to subscribe toSports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Daily Rings, my daily podcast where Dan Gartland and I recap every sport every day. Join now so you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be with us in time to put a bow on the entire Olympics next when they are over.\\u00c2  Here\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s what I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be watching Friday, August 9.  This is not a comprehensive list;visit Olympics.comfor a full schedule. All events will stream live on Peacock. I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll also be tweeting out a schedule of medal events, Team USA games and other favorites each day.  My Day 14 Olympics viewing guide! It's Friday, and there are *A TON* of medals being handed out#Paris2024pic.twitter.com/igS6FFi0L5  It has been much discussed over the past few years, but breaking will finally make its Olympic debut over the next two days. Yes, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s breakdancing. Unlike gymnastics, they will have to freestyle with no control over what music is played.  You may be expecting young athletes, but the U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s team (they actually call them B-Girls) is led by 35-year-old Sunni Choi, who won a silver at the 2022 World Games.  A round robin starts at 10 a.m. ET, and the finals start shortly after 3 p.m. ET. The B-Boys will compete Saturday. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going to be interesting, and people are going to be talking about it, so you might as well check it out for yourself to see what all the fuss is about.  Friday\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s schedule has two big games with medals on the line. The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s bronze game is between Spain and Germany at 9 a.m. ET.\\u00c2  Then we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see the gold medal game to wrap up the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s competition at noon ET. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll be the host country, France, against Spain. Spain won silver in Tokyo, but France has not won a medal in men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s soccer since taking gold back in 1984.  And finally, we have just two days left of beach volleyball. On Friday they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll play the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s bronze and gold medal matches, followed the next day by the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s bronze and gold matches.  All four of Team USA\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s pairs were knocked out before the medal rounds, but it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll still be great to watch the conclusion of what has been a fun tournament in an iconic location right at the foot of the Eiffel Tower.\\u00c2  Teams from Switzerland and Australia will battle for bronze at 3 p.m. ET, followed by the gold medal match between teams from Canada and Brazil at 4:30.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Mitch Goldich is a senior editor for Sports Illustrated, mostly focused on the NFL. He has also covered the Olympics extensively and written on a variety of sports since joining SI in 2014. His work has been published by The New York Times, Baseball Prospectus and Food & Wine, among other outlets. Goldich has a bachelor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from Lehigh University and a master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s in journalism from the Medill School at Northwestern University. He is a Philly native, now living in Boston, and he invented and popularized the octopus, when the same player scores a touchdown and the ensuing two-point conversion.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"